The paper proposes a sequence labeling framework that utilizes sparse indicator features derived from dense distributed word representations. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the natural language processing (NLP) sub-category of computer science, which is cs.CL. Additionally, the paper uses neural word embeddings, which are a common tool in machine learning and deep learning, suggesting that it could also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) or artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also evaluates its proposed model on part-of-speech tagging and named entity recognition tasks, which are common NLP tasks, further supporting the likelihood of cs.CL as the primary sub-category. Finally, the paper's use of sparse coding could also suggest a potential fit with the neural networks (cs.NE) or computer vision (cs.CV) sub-categories, although these are less likely than the others mentioned.
